My intention was to try to stake some claim in the centre. I knew I wanted my knight to be on f6 pretty quickly to protect h5 from his queen and to prevent any pawn advance from f5. It would also pressure the centre.
Schliemann defence, Berger variation. Though I am unsure of the full implications of that. This move is probably to protect the bishop and the pawn on e4

He was forced to do something about that pawn. With it here I can attack it with my lsb and it can't be too easily defended, as g4 wouldn't be good for king castling and B d3 blocks in his d pawn as well as limiting his dsb
